TY  - JOUR
AU  - Cachon, Gérard P.
AU  - Camerer, Colin F.
T1  - Loss-Avoidance and Forward Induction in Experimental Coordination Games
PY  - 1996
Y1  - 1996/02/01
DO  - 10.2307/2946661
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 111
IS  - 1
SP  - 165
EP  - 194
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - We report experiments on how players select among multiple Pareto-ranked equilibria in a coordination game. Subjects initially choose inefficient equilibria. Charging a fee to play (which makes initial equilibria money-losing) creates coordination on better equilibria. When fees are optional, improved coordination is consistent with forward induction. But coordination improves even when subjects must pay the fee (forward induction does not apply). Subjects appear to use a “loss-avoidance” selection principle: they expect others to avoid strategies that always result in losses. Loss-avoidance implies that “mental accounting” of outcomes can affect choices in games.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.2307/2946661
ER  - 



